Template Ioslide Walkthrough

Titles

See ioslides manual at: https://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/ioslides_presentation_format

Titles with a single # will generate a blank screen containing the title only, useful for section breaks. Titles with two ## will start a new slide with the following text as the heading.

Titles

Subtitles

You can add a subtitle to a slide or section by including text after the pipe (|) character. For example:

## Titles | Subtitles

Incremental Bullets

Incremental Bullets

  • Format the front matter with incremental: true to enable incremental bullets.

output:
ioslides_presentation:
incremental: true

If you want to render bullets incrementally for some slides but not others you can use this syntax:
> - like
> - this

Incremental Bullets

Otherwise use syntax:
- like
- this

and bullets will appear:

  • like
  • this

Images

A R generated plot

To centre an image include the following in the r chunk header:

{r, echo = FALSE, out.extra = ‘class=“centre”’}

A linked image

An image can be added, either from a local file or external URL, by using the include_graphics() function inside a chunk:

```{r, echo = FALSE, out.extra = ‘class=“centre” style=“width: 300px;”’}
include_graphics(“assets/images/logo800.jpg”)

```

In-line figures

In-line figures can be placed in a paragraphy by including the following code into the R chunk header:

{r, out.extra = ‘style=“float: left; width: 250px; margin: 10px;”’}

float: left; can be either left or right. The image size can be manipultaed by changing the width: 250px; text, and the margin size around the image can be manipulated with margin: 10px;.

Slide modifications

2 Columns

Layout

Slides can be modified by placing content inside HTML div tags with class arguments:

<div class=“col2”></div>

1 one
2 two
3 three
4 four
5 five
6 six
7 seven
8 eight
9 nine

3 Columns

Layout

<div class=“col3”></div>

1 one
2 two
3 three
4 four
5 five
6 six
7 seven
8 eight
9 nine

Text Size

Formatting

Font-size can be manipulated within a slide by placing the text within div tags with class=“small” or class=“large”.

This is an example of small text:

<div class=“small”></div>

This is the normal default font size.

This is an example of large text:

<div class=“large”></div>

Multiple Formatting Tags

Multiple classes can be assigned to a single div:

<div class=“col3 large”></div>

1 one
2 two
3 three
4 four
5 five
6 six
7 seven
8 eight
9 nine
